<TITLE> Shipping ministry refers Matin case to ACC </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Kamran Reza Chowdhury and Prodip Chowdhury bdnews24.com Correspondents Dhaka, Sept 02 (bdnews24.com)The shipping ministry has sent the parliamentary findings on former adviser M A Matin's alleged irregularities in awarding a container handling work at Chittagong port to the Anticorruption Commission for legal action. "On Tuesday, we sent the parliamentary probe report coupled with the relevant documents to the Anticorruption Commission for taking legal actions against M A Matin," Shajahan Khan, shipping minister, told bdnews24.com on Wednesday night. ACC chairman Golam Rahman confirmed receiving the documents. "We have received the findings. They urged us to take legal actions against him (Matin)," Rahman told bdnews24.com on Wednesday night. "The Anticorruption Commission will investigate the charges and take the necessary action," he said. The parliamentary standing committee on shipping ministry on Aug 30 approved the parliamentary findings on irregularities in awarding container handling work at Chittagong container terminal to a 'novice' company, Echhaq Brothers, on his last day in office on Jan 6, 2009. The committee on May 27 formed a four-member parliamentary probe body, headed by Awami League MP Shah Alam, to investigate the deal. Awami League Shamsul Huq Chowdhry and Nazrul Islam Babu and the BNP's Mostofa Kamal Pasha are the other members of the probe body. The probe body identified nine officials including Matin over the alleged irregularities. bd
